text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!The Indian Accent in Media%0a%0a:Author: sanjana_m%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThis article looks at one specific aspect of the Indian accent and how it is made fun of and used to perpetuate stereotypes.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://vm.tiktok.com/ZMeQuMuDd/%0a%0aIn this example, the pronunciations of the words “watermelon” and “passport” indicates that a characteristic of the accent is the non-usage of [r]. Throughout TikTok, TV shows, and in standup comedy, people who are portraying the Indian accent often use [ɾ], [ɽ], or [r] depending on the word. This would be considered as consonant substitution, which people are decrying as ungrammatical.%0a%0aThis TikTok, which is a criticism of Indian English, as well as others, are just some examples of this. In more mainstream media, the Indian accent, specifically the issues with the [r] sound are used for comedic purposes. For example, in the show Phineas and Ferb, the character Baljeet has a strong accent and is known to be the less social more studious character, following Indian stereotypes. In Jessie, the character Ravi (the Indian-American actor actual speaks Standardized English) has an accent and is often the awkward anti-social kid. The stereotype of Indians as show owners is portrayed with an Indian accent by an American actor who plays Apu. Many other shows, like the Big Bang Theory, which involves an Indian character who cannot talk to women, perpetuates these stereotypes as well. %0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-000655-409910#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Association of Indian Accent with the Nerdy Character %0a-> - SubhasishM%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI think the Indian accent in particular has become associative of a certain character as you mentioned. I was born in India and my parents have their own Bengali accents, but even I have come to associate the stereotypical accent we have on TV with the archetype of character you described.%0a%0aIt's unfortunate that this has become so normalized in our society, and I think it is much more likely that people in America who come across those with the stereotypical Indian accent immediately can assign a character to them. While this phenomenon isn't unique to Indian accents, I think that Indians are one group that are among the most negatively affected by this societal discrimination.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-000655-409910#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: D:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
